&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;span face="Calibri"&gt;&lt;span&gt;Problem in Words&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;span face="Calibri"&gt;&lt;span&gt;10 times x equals y&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;span face="Calibri"&gt;&lt;span&gt;X divided by 6 equals y&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;span face="Calibri"&gt;&lt;span&gt;3 times x plus 10 equals y&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;span face="Calibri"&gt;&lt;span&gt;4 times x plus x equals y&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;span face="Calibri"&gt;&lt;span&gt;5 times x equals y&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;span face="Calibri"&gt;&lt;span&gt;Equations&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;span face="Calibri"&gt;&lt;span&gt;Y =3x +10&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;span face="Calibri"&gt;&lt;span&gt;X / 6 = y&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;span face="Calibri"&gt;&lt;span&gt;Y = 10x&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;span face="Calibri"&gt;&lt;span&gt;4x + x =y&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span face="Calibri"&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;span&gt;This lesson can be differentiated in multiple ways&lt;/span&gt;:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;span face="Calibri"&gt;&lt;span&gt;Lower Level&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;span face="Calibri"&gt;&lt;span&gt;Provide all of the pieces – the completed table, the problem written in words, and the equation, so the students can match them, rather than coming up with them on their own&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;span face="Calibri"&gt;&lt;span&gt;Focus on writing out the rule in words rather than the equations&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;span face="Calibri"&gt;&lt;span&gt;Use less complex numbers&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;span face="Calibri"&gt;&lt;span&gt;Higher Level&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;span face="Calibri"&gt;&lt;span&gt;Provide opportunities for the students to produce missing parts of the table, or the equation, or the problem in words&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;span face="Calibri"&gt;&lt;span&gt;Discuss relationships between different notations, such as 3x + 10 = y and x +x +x +10 +y&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;span face="Calibri"&gt;Make the rules more complex such as, y = x&lt;sup&gt;2 &lt;/sup&gt;+ (6 – 3)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;span face="Calibri"&gt;Source: Adapted from Schmitt, M., Steinbeck, M., Donovan, T., Merson, M. (2005). Seeking patterns, building rules: Algebraic thinking.  Teacher Book.  Key Curriculum Press: Emeryville, CA.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
